Lets plot the data using ggplot to see what were working with.

ggplot() + geom_sf(data = boston_water)

Now, Id look to visualize the area of these different bodies of water using gradient fills. First, lets set the area attribute to the log of the area so that the different areas or more easily differentiable.

boston_water$ShapeSTAre <- log(
  as.numeric(
    as.character(
      boston_water$ShapeSTAre)) + 10)

Now, lets create a chlorepleth showing the areas of different bodies water.

water <- ggplot(boston_water) + 
  geom_sf() + 
  aes(fill=ShapeSTAre) + 
  scale_fill_gradient2(midpoint = median(boston_water$ShapeSTAre), mid = "red", high = "blue") +
  labs(fill = "Log_10 Area")
water

Lets take four different subsets of the data, each representing a major type of body of water, and plot each of them.

ggplot() + geom_sf(data = subset(boston_water, TYPE == "POND"))

ggplot() + geom_sf(data = subset(boston_water, TYPE == "STREAM"))

ggplot() + geom_sf(data = subset(boston_water, TYPE == "WETAREA"))

ggplot() + geom_sf(data = subset(boston_water, TYPE == "SHORELINE"))
